{
  "text": "Mixed Ionic-Electron Conduction (MIEC) occurs in materials that conduct both electronic charges and ions. Recently, Gopalakrishnan et al. [CITATION_1] reported selectors based on Cu-containing MIEC materials, where the MIEC layer is sandwiched between an inert bottom electrode (BEC) and top electrode (TEC). The applied voltage leads toa transient Cu ion movement, followed by steady electron/hole diffusion current, which generates strong non-linear I-V characteristics. With an optimized CMP process [CITATION_2] - [CITATION_3] , the integrated MIEC selectors in large 512x1024 arrays at 100 % yield was achieved. The MIEC devices were integrated using diode-in-via method as shown in fig. 24 (a) [CITATION_4] . Bipolar DC I-V characteristics show \u223c1 pA leakage current near 0V and wide voltage range \u223c1.5 V with below 10 nA. Pulse measurements show that the MIEC devices can deliver maximum currents of over 100 A [CITATION_5] , which corresponds to a drive current density over 10MA/cm 2 for the reported selector size. Thus, MIEC based selectors can offer the desirable combination of low off leakage current and high on current. At low-current (<10 A) stress condition, the MIEC selector can withstand over 1010 endurance cycles [CITATION_6] , [CITATION_7] . At high-current stress, the voltage margin (V m ) degrades and eventually the selector becomes short-circuited, as observed in fig. 24 (b) . TEM/EELS analysis implies endurance failure is possibly related to accumulation of Cu ions in the MIEC material [CITATION_8] . Despite a Cu accumulation failure, another concern for MIEC-based selector is the low operating voltage range (or voltage margin). This makes MIEC selector less suitable for most of the resistive switching elements, which need to be programmed at relatively large voltages [CITATION_9] , [CITATION_10] . ",
